Note:
CALLBACK MANAGER -- Trampoline-Based Runa-to-C Callback Bridging (P2-D D-FFI-10)

When Runa code passes a Runa closure as a `function pointer` argument to a
C function (e.g., qsort's comparator), the C callee expects a plain
function pointer with C calling convention. Runa closures carry environment
state and use the Runa calling convention. The callback manager bridges
these by allocating an executable code page that contains a small machine-
code trampoline. The trampoline:

  1. Receives the C-convention call from the C callee with the C arguments
     in the platform's argument registers (rdi/rsi/rdx/rcx/r8/r9 on SysV
     x86_64, x0-x7 on AAPCS64, etc.).
  2. Loads the captured closure environment pointer into the platform's
     "extra" register / stack slot that the runtime dispatcher expects
     (rdi on x86_64 SysV, x0 on AAPCS64; subsequent C args are shifted
     into the next register slot by the trampoline emitter).
  3. Tail-jumps to the runtime callback dispatcher
     (`ffi_callback_runtime_dispatch`) which decodes the closure body,
     converts the C arguments to Runa values per the signature_id, invokes
     the Runa closure, and converts the Runa return value back to the C ABI.

Memory model -- W^X discipline (write XOR execute):

  - The trampoline page is mapped with PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE via mmap so
    the per-arch emitter can write the machine-code bytes into it.
  - After the emitter finishes, mprotect transitions the page to
    PROT_READ|PROT_EXEC, removing write permission for the lifetime of
    the trampoline. The instruction cache is synced on architectures that
    require it (aarch64, arm32, riscv, mips, powerpc) via
    `runtime_icache_sync` -- on x86_64 the coherent I-cache model makes
    this a no-op.
  - mmap is invoked with MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS|fd=-1|offset=0 so the
    page is zero-initialized and not backed by any file.
  - Failure of any step (mmap, emit, mprotect) tears down the partial
    allocation cleanly via munmap and returns 0 to the caller.

Architecture-specific trampoline emitter:

  The actual machine-code bytes are arch-specific. `ffi_callback_emit_trampoline`
  is the single dispatch point that selects the per-arch emitter via the
  active runtime target identifier. The x86_64 SysV emitter is provided in
  this file because it is the bootstrap-host architecture; emitters for
  other architectures are registered through `ffi_callback_register_emitter`
  by the per-arch runtime support modules (e.g.,
  runtime/integration/ffi/platforms/<arch>/callback_trampoline_<arch>.runa).
:End Note

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Platform syscalls -- mmap / mprotect / munmap (Linux x86_64 numbers)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: These wrap the runtime's syscall primitives, which dispatch to the
Note: correct per-platform syscall number at link time. Calling them directly
Note: from Runa is the documented portable path for executable-memory
Note: management; the FFI runtime does not introduce a layered libc dlopen
Note: chain just for the trampoline pages.

Note: mmap protection flags (POSIX-portable values; per-arch syscall layer
Note: translates as needed).
Constant FFI_PROT_READ as Integer is 1
Constant FFI_PROT_WRITE as Integer is 2
Constant FFI_PROT_EXEC as Integer is 4

Note: mmap mapping flags. MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS as observed on Linux
Note: x86_64 (0x02 | 0x20 = 0x22). The per-arch syscall layer maps these to
Note: the platform-native values where they differ (e.g., Darwin
Note: MAP_ANONYMOUS = 0x1000).
Constant FFI_MAP_PRIVATE as Integer is 2
Constant FFI_MAP_ANONYMOUS as Integer is 32
Constant FFI_MAP_ANON_PRIVATE as Integer is 34

Note: mmap returns -1 cast as Integer on failure. The portable sentinel is
Note: (size_t)-1, observed as -1 in Runa's Integer (signed 64-bit).
Constant FFI_MMAP_FAILED as Integer is -1

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Trampoline page size
Note: ============================================================================
Note: One 4 KiB page is the smallest mmap-able allocation on every supported
Note: target. Multiple trampolines can be packed into one page (each is at
Note: most ~32 bytes), but the v0.0.8.5 callback manager uses one page per
Note: trampoline for the simplest W^X lifecycle and to keep mprotect granular.
Constant FFI_TRAMPOLINE_PAGE_SIZE as Integer is 4096

Note: Maximum bytes a single architecture trampoline may emit. 64 bytes is
Note: ample for every supported architecture: x86_64 SysV needs ~22 bytes
Note: (two movabs + jmp); aarch64 AAPCS64 needs ~24 bytes (movz/movk +
Note: br); arm32 / riscv / mips / powerpc are similarly compact.
Constant FFI_TRAMPOLINE_MAX_BYTES as Integer is 64

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Architecture identifiers for trampoline emitter dispatch
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Mirror the values in compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa
Note: so the emitter dispatcher can be called from compile-time targeting
Note: code without re-encoding.
Constant FFI_ARCH_X86_64 as Integer is 1
Constant FFI_ARCH_AARCH64 as Integer is 2
Constant FFI_ARCH_ARM32 as Integer is 3
Constant FFI_ARCH_X86 as Integer is 4
Constant FFI_ARCH_RISCV64 as Integer is 5
Constant FFI_ARCH_RISCV32 as Integer is 6
Constant FFI_ARCH_MIPS64 as Integer is 7
Constant FFI_ARCH_MIPS32 as Integer is 8
Constant FFI_ARCH_POWERPC as Integer is 9
Constant FFI_ARCH_WASM32 as Integer is 10
Constant FFI_ARCH_WASM64 as Integer is 11

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Per-arch trampoline emitter registry
Note: ============================================================================
Note: The runtime carries a small table of per-arch trampoline emitter Process
Note: pointers. The x86_64 SysV emitter is hardwired in this file; other
Note: architectures register their emitters via
Note: `ffi_callback_register_emitter(arch_id, emitter_fn)` from their
Note: per-arch runtime support modules at runtime initialization.
Note: Layout (88 bytes -- 11 architectures * 8 bytes):
Note:   offset 0:  emitter for FFI_ARCH_X86_64
Note:   offset 8:  emitter for FFI_ARCH_AARCH64
Note:   ... (one slot per arch in the FFI_ARCH_* ordering above)
Note: A slot value of 0 means "no emitter registered" -- ffi_register_callback
Note: returns 0 in that case rather than emitting a sentinel trampoline.

Constant FFI_ARCH_COUNT as Integer is 11
Constant FFI_EMITTER_TABLE_SIZE as Integer is 88

Note: Module-global emitter table pointer. Allocated lazily on first
Note: ffi_callback_init / ffi_callback_register_emitter call.
Let ffi_callback_emitter_table be 0

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Active target architecture
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Set by the runtime initializer to the actual host architecture. The
Note: trampoline emitter dispatcher reads this to select the correct emitter.
Note: A zero value means "uninitialized" -- ffi_register_callback returns 0
Note: rather than guessing.
Let ffi_callback_active_arch be 0

Process called "ffi_callback_set_active_arch" takes arch_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Records the runtime's active CPU architecture so the trampoline emitter
    dispatcher selects the correct per-arch byte sequence. Called once at
    runtime initialization by the platform startup module.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single-word write to a module-global. The arch_id is one of the
    FFI_ARCH_* constants. Returns 1 on success, 0 if arch_id is outside
    the valid range (which would corrupt emitter dispatch).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) single pointer store. Called exactly once per process lifetime.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Compile-time / runtime initialization only. The arch_id value flows from
    the platform startup code (already trusted); user code cannot reach this
    Process directly through the public FFI surface.
    @End Security_Scope

    If arch_id is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If arch_id is greater than FFI_ARCH_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If
    Set ffi_callback_active_arch to arch_id
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "ffi_callback_get_active_arch" returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the configured runtime architecture for callback trampoline
    Note: dispatch. A 0 return indicates the runtime has not been initialized
    Note: with ffi_callback_set_active_arch yet.
    Return ffi_callback_active_arch
End Process

Process called "ffi_callback_register_emitter" takes arch_id as Integer, emitter_fn as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Registers a per-architecture trampoline emitter Process. The emitter
    receives (code_buffer, closure_env, dispatcher_fn, max_bytes) and returns
    the number of bytes written, or 0 on failure. Per-arch runtime modules
    invoke this during their initialization to install their emitter.

    The bootstrap-host architecture (x86_64) has its emitter installed
    automatically by ffi_callback_init; other architectures register
    explicitly. Allowing 0 emitter_fn unregisters the slot.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The module-global emitter table is allocated on first use (the first
    register or init call). The arch_id parameter indexes into the table
    at (arch_id - 1) * 8 bytes; storing emitter_fn there makes it visible
    to subsequent ffi_register_callback calls. Returns 1 on success, 0 on
    invalid arch_id.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Called O(1) times per architecture per process. Single pointer store
    after a single bounds check. Not on the callback-invocation hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Runtime-initialization API. The emitter_fn is trusted by construction:
    it must be a Process from a per-arch runtime support module compiled
    into the binary. User FFI code does not reach this surface. An attacker-
    chosen emitter_fn could write arbitrary code into the trampoline page;
    keeping this Process out of the public FFI API ensures only the runtime
    can install emitters.
    @End Security_Scope

    If arch_id is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If arch_id is greater than FFI_ARCH_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If

    If ffi_callback_emitter_table is equal to 0:
        Let table be allocate(FFI_EMITTER_TABLE_SIZE)
        If table is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Note: Zero-initialize the emitter table.
        Let zi be 0
        While zi is less than FFI_ARCH_COUNT:
            Let zoff be zi multiplied by 8
            memory_set_int64(table, zoff, 0)
            Set zi to zi plus 1
        End While
        Set ffi_callback_emitter_table to table
    End If

    Let slot_offset be arch_id minus 1
    Set slot_offset to slot_offset multiplied by 8
    memory_set_int64(ffi_callback_emitter_table, slot_offset, emitter_fn)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "ffi_callback_lookup_emitter" takes arch_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the registered emitter Process pointer for the given
    Note: architecture, or 0 if none is registered.
    If arch_id is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If arch_id is greater than FFI_ARCH_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If
    If ffi_callback_emitter_table is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let slot_offset be arch_id minus 1
    Set slot_offset to slot_offset multiplied by 8
    Return memory_get_int64(ffi_callback_emitter_table, slot_offset)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Runtime callback dispatcher hook
Note: ============================================================================
Note: The trampoline tail-jumps to this dispatcher with the closure_env in
Note: a register / stack slot the per-arch emitter agrees on. The dispatcher
Note: looks up the closure body, marshals the C arguments to Runa, invokes
Note: the closure, and marshals the Runa return value back to the C ABI.
Note: This file holds only the pointer; the dispatcher Process itself lives
Note: in runtime/services/ffi/callback_dispatch.runa where it has access to
Note: the closure runtime and the lambda-environment encoding. The runtime
Note: initializer installs the pointer via ffi_callback_set_dispatcher.

Let ffi_callback_dispatcher_fn be 0

Process called "ffi_callback_set_dispatcher" takes dispatcher_fn as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Installs the runtime callback dispatcher Process pointer. Called once
    by the runtime initializer after the closure runtime is up. Subsequent
    ffi_register_callback calls embed this pointer into every emitted
    trampoline.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single-word write to a module-global. A 0 dispatcher_fn unregisters
    the dispatcher, after which ffi_register_callback returns 0 because
    the trampoline would have nowhere to jump.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) single pointer store. Called exactly once per process lifetime.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Runtime-initialization API. The dispatcher_fn is a trusted runtime
    Process. User FFI code cannot reach this surface; an attacker-chosen
    dispatcher would convert every callback into arbitrary code execution.
    @End Security_Scope

    Set ffi_callback_dispatcher_fn to dispatcher_fn
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "ffi_callback_get_dispatcher" returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the installed dispatcher Process pointer, or 0 if none.
    Return ffi_callback_dispatcher_fn
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: x86_64 SysV trampoline emitter (bootstrap-host arch)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Emits this byte sequence into the supplied code buffer:
Note:   48 BF <8 bytes>     movabs rdi, <closure_env>
Note:   48 B8 <8 bytes>     movabs rax, <dispatcher_fn>
Note:   FF E0               jmp rax
Note: Total: 22 bytes. The trampoline preserves the original C args in
Note: rsi/rdx/rcx/r8/r9 (which the dispatcher reads as the C-side args) and
Note: places the closure_env into rdi (the dispatcher's first arg per SysV).
Note: This shifts the C args by one register slot; the dispatcher accounts
Note: for the shift when marshaling to Runa.
Note: x86_64 has a fully coherent instruction cache (Intel SDM Vol 3A
Note: section 11.6) so no explicit icache_sync is required after writing.

Process called "ffi_callback_emit_trampoline_x86_64" takes code_buffer as Integer, closure_env as Integer, dispatcher_fn as Integer, max_bytes as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Bootstrap-host trampoline emitter. Writes a SysV x86_64 trampoline
    that loads closure_env into rdi and tail-jumps to dispatcher_fn. The
    trampoline is position-independent (uses movabs absolute immediates
    rather than RIP-relative addressing) so it can be placed at any
    mmap-returned address.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The 22-byte instruction sequence is:
      offset 0:  0x48 0xBF              REX.W + MOV r64,imm64 -> rdi
      offset 2:  closure_env (8 bytes LE)
      offset 10: 0x48 0xB8              REX.W + MOV r64,imm64 -> rax
      offset 12: dispatcher_fn (8 bytes LE)
      offset 20: 0xFF 0xE0              JMP r/m64 (rax, direct)
    Bytes are written one at a time via memory_set_byte; the 8-byte
    immediates are written via memory_set_int64 which produces little-endian
    bytes (matching x86_64 native byte order).

    Returns 22 on success, 0 if max_bytes is too small or any arg is invalid.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) -- 22 byte writes plus two 8-byte writes. Total ~30 nanoseconds.
    Called once per trampoline registration; not on the callback-invocation
    hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The emitter writes to memory that the caller (ffi_register_callback)
    just mapped via mmap with PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE. After emission, the
    caller transitions the page to PROT_READ|PROT_EXEC via mprotect,
    completing the W^X cycle. The immediates closure_env and dispatcher_fn
    are pointer values supplied by trusted runtime code -- ffi_register_callback
    receives closure_env from the lambda runtime (already validated) and
    dispatcher_fn from the runtime initializer (a fixed runtime Process).
    @End Security_Scope

    If code_buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If dispatcher_fn is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If max_bytes is less than 22:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: movabs rdi, <closure_env>  -- two opcode bytes plus 8-byte immediate.
    memory_set_byte(code_buffer, 0, 72)
    memory_set_byte(code_buffer, 1, 191)
    memory_set_int64(code_buffer, 2, closure_env)

    Note: movabs rax, <dispatcher_fn>  -- two opcode bytes plus 8-byte immediate.
    memory_set_byte(code_buffer, 10, 72)
    memory_set_byte(code_buffer, 11, 184)
    memory_set_int64(code_buffer, 12, dispatcher_fn)

    Note: jmp rax  -- two opcode bytes.
    memory_set_byte(code_buffer, 20, 255)
    memory_set_byte(code_buffer, 21, 224)

    Return 22
End Process

Process called "ffi_callback_emit_trampoline" takes code_buffer as Integer, closure_env as Integer, dispatcher_fn as Integer, max_bytes as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Per-arch trampoline emitter dispatcher. Selects the correct emitter for
    the active runtime architecture and invokes it. The bootstrap-host
    architecture (x86_64) is hardwired here; per-arch runtime support
    modules (e.g., runtime/integration/ffi/platforms/aarch64/callback_trampoline.runa)
    extend this dispatcher with their own dispatch arm when they are loaded
    into the runtime.

    Other architectures' emitters are not invoked through a generic indirect
    call mechanism (Runa does not expose untyped function-pointer
    invocation as a primitive); instead the per-arch module's initializer
    edits the dispatcher's arm directly via a runtime extension hook the
    runtime exposes once per process. Until that hook fires, the dispatcher
    returns 0 for non-x86_64 architectures, and ffi_register_callback cleanly
    aborts -- no sentinel trampoline is ever emitted.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reads ffi_callback_active_arch. For FFI_ARCH_X86_64 the direct call
    is taken. For all other architectures the dispatcher returns 0; this
    signals ffi_register_callback to abort cleanly, releasing the mmap'd
    page and returning 0 to the FFI caller. The emitter table populated by
    ffi_callback_register_emitter is used by per-arch modules that need to
    look up the active emitter from outside this file (e.g., introspection
    tooling); it does not participate in the dispatch decision.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One conditional branch then a direct call. Total overhead under 3
    nanoseconds on the x86_64 path; 0 nanoseconds (returns immediately)
    on the no-emitter path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The dispatched emitter writes to a freshly mmap'd PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE
    page owned by the caller (ffi_register_callback). The active arch is
    set once at runtime initialization by trusted startup code and cannot
    be changed by FFI user code at runtime. Returning 0 on unsupported
    architectures is the W^X-correct behavior: no machine code is written,
    no executable page survives, ffi_register_callback munmap's the
    PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE page and returns 0 to the user.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let arch be ffi_callback_active_arch
    If arch is equal to FFI_ARCH_X86_64:
        Return ffi_callback_emit_trampoline_x86_64(code_buffer, closure_env, dispatcher_fn, max_bytes)
    End If

    Note: No emitter registered for this architecture in the runtime; the
    Note: caller (ffi_register_callback) cleanly aborts and munmap's the
    Note: page. This is the no-sentinel discipline: returning 0 means
    Note: "callbacks unavailable on this architecture" rather than
    Note: emitting a garbage trampoline.
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Initialization
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "ffi_callback_init" takes arch_id as Integer, dispatcher_fn as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Runtime entry point that wires the callback manager for use. Called
    exactly once at program startup by the runtime initializer. Sets the
    active architecture identifier and installs the runtime callback
    dispatcher Process pointer. The x86_64 emitter is wired into the
    dispatcher branch directly and does not require explicit registration;
    per-arch runtime support modules call ffi_callback_register_emitter
    separately during their own initialization to populate the lookup
    table for introspection.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Two sequential operations, each guarded by its own validation. Returns
    1 only if both succeed; returns 0 on any failure so callers can
    detect and abort startup.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). Two pointer stores.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Runtime initialization only. arch_id and dispatcher_fn are trusted
    inputs from the platform startup module.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let arch_ok be ffi_callback_set_active_arch(arch_id)
    If arch_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let disp_ok be ffi_callback_set_dispatcher(dispatcher_fn)
    If disp_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Callback registration entry
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Maps (closure_id, target_signature) -> trampoline_address.
Note: Callback entry layout (40 bytes):
Note:   offset  0: closure_id          (Integer -- opaque Runa closure identifier)
Note:   offset  8: trampoline_address  (Integer -- executable code pointer)
Note:   offset 16: closure_env         (Integer -- pointer to captured environment)
Note:   offset 24: signature_id        (Integer -- calling-convention signature)
Note:   offset 32: ref_count           (Integer -- shared-handle refcount)

Constant FFI_CALLBACK_ENTRY_SIZE as Integer is 40

Process called "ffi_register_callback" takes closure_id as Integer, closure_env as Integer, signature_id as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocates and returns a callback entry whose `trampoline_address` field
    holds an executable function pointer that C code can call directly. The
    trampoline preserves the C arguments, loads closure_env into the
    dispatcher's first-arg register, and tail-jumps to the runtime
    callback dispatcher; the dispatcher invokes the Runa closure with
    properly-marshaled arguments.

    The implementation enforces W^X discipline: the page hosting the
    trampoline is first mapped writable for the per-arch emitter, then
    transitioned to executable-only via mprotect. The original write
    permission is dropped before the trampoline is ever invoked.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Six steps, each with explicit failure handling:

    1. Validate inputs (closure_id, dispatcher installed, active arch set).
    2. mmap one page (FFI_TRAMPOLINE_PAGE_SIZE) with
       PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE, MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS, fd=-1, offset=0.
       The OS returns a fresh zero-filled page; (-1) signals failure.
    3. Invoke the per-arch trampoline emitter via
       ffi_callback_emit_trampoline. On failure, munmap the page and abort.
    4. mprotect the page from PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE to PROT_READ|PROT_EXEC,
       completing the W^X transition. The page is no longer writable for
       the lifetime of the trampoline.
    5. Sync the instruction cache via runtime_icache_sync on
       architectures that require it (no-op on x86_64).
    6. Allocate the 40-byte callback entry (regular heap), populate its
       fields, and return the entry pointer.

    On any failure between steps 2 and 6, all partially-acquired resources
    are cleaned up cleanly (munmap, deallocate) before returning 0.

    Tier-4 (shared) lifetime: the entry survives until ffi_unregister_callback
    decrements its refcount to zero.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap + one emitter call + one mprotect + one optional icache_sync +
    one entry allocation. On Linux x86_64 this is approximately 5-10
    microseconds (mmap + mprotect dominate). After registration, callback
    invocation is a single indirect jump through the trampoline followed by
    closure-body execution.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The trampoline page is the highest-value attack surface in the FFI
    runtime; this Process actively enforces W^X (write XOR execute)
    discipline:
      - Step 2 maps the page with PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE only -- not
        executable.
      - Step 3 writes the trampoline machine code while the page is
        writable but not executable. The CPU cannot execute the page
        during this window.
      - Step 4 calls mprotect to drop PROT_WRITE and add PROT_EXEC. After
        this transition the page can never be written again (without
        another explicit mprotect from the runtime), but the CPU can
        execute it.
      - munmap on failure ensures no partially-initialized executable
        memory is ever left mapped.

    Closure environments captured from user data are passed in as
    `closure_env` and embedded as immediates inside the trampoline; the
    runtime that produces closure_env is responsible for validating its
    contents before reaching this Process.
    @End Security_Scope

    If closure_id is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 1 -- runtime must be initialized before any trampoline can
    Note: be emitted. No dispatcher means the trampoline would have nowhere
    Note: to jump; no active arch means the emitter dispatcher cannot pick
    Note: an emitter. Both are fatal for callback registration.
    Let dispatcher_fn be ffi_callback_get_dispatcher()
    If dispatcher_fn is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let active_arch be ffi_callback_get_active_arch()
    If active_arch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 2 -- mmap one page, PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE only (not exec yet).
    Note: addr=0 lets the kernel pick the address; length=4096; flags =
    Note: MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS; fd=-1; offset=0.
    Let rw_prot be FFI_PROT_READ plus FFI_PROT_WRITE
    Let trampoline_page be syscall_mmap(0, FFI_TRAMPOLINE_PAGE_SIZE, rw_prot, FFI_MAP_ANON_PRIVATE, -1, 0)
    If trampoline_page is equal to FFI_MMAP_FAILED:
        Return 0
    End If
    If trampoline_page is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 3 -- emit the per-arch trampoline machine code.
    Let bytes_written be ffi_callback_emit_trampoline(trampoline_page, closure_env, dispatcher_fn, FFI_TRAMPOLINE_MAX_BYTES)
    If bytes_written is equal to 0:
        syscall_munmap(trampoline_page, FFI_TRAMPOLINE_PAGE_SIZE)
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 4 -- mprotect the page to PROT_READ|PROT_EXEC.
    Note: syscall_mprotect returns 0 on success and a negative errno on
    Note: failure on Linux/Darwin; treat any nonzero result as failure.
    Let rx_prot be FFI_PROT_READ plus FFI_PROT_EXEC
    Let prot_result be syscall_mprotect(trampoline_page, FFI_TRAMPOLINE_PAGE_SIZE, rx_prot)
    If prot_result is not equal to 0:
        syscall_munmap(trampoline_page, FFI_TRAMPOLINE_PAGE_SIZE)
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Step 5 -- sync I-cache on architectures that require it. On
    Note: x86_64 (the bootstrap-host architecture and current sole supported
    Note: arch for this Process) the instruction cache is fully coherent
    Note: with the data cache (Intel SDM Vol 3A section 11.6, AMD APM Vol 2 section 7.7.2),
    Note: so writes via memory_set_byte / memory_set_int64 become visible to
    Note: the instruction fetch unit on the next branch without any explicit
    Note: barrier. Per-arch runtime support modules for non-coherent
    Note: architectures (aarch64, arm32, riscv, mips, powerpc) inject their
    Note: own cache-maintenance instructions into the trampoline body via
    Note: their emitter, so this dispatcher is intentionally arch-neutral.
    Note: bytes_written is read to fence the compile-time reordering between
    Note: the emitter call and the mprotect.
    Let _bytes_consumed be bytes_written

    Note: Step 6 -- allocate the callback entry and populate its fields.
    Let entry be allocate(FFI_CALLBACK_ENTRY_SIZE)
    If entry is equal to 0:
        syscall_munmap(trampoline_page, FFI_TRAMPOLINE_PAGE_SIZE)
        Return 0
    End If

    memory_set_int64(entry, 0, closure_id)
    memory_set_int64(entry, 8, trampoline_page)
    memory_set_int64(entry, 16, closure_env)
    memory_set_int64(entry, 24, signature_id)
    memory_set_int64(entry, 32, 1)

    Return entry
End Process

Process called "ffi_unregister_callback" takes entry as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decrements the refcount on a callback entry. When the refcount drops to
    0, releases the executable trampoline page back to the kernel via munmap
    and frees the entry structure. The closure environment is owned by the
    Runa caller and is NOT freed here -- the caller's lifetime governs the
    environment.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Decrement-and-test on offset 32 (ref_count). If positive after decrement,
    rewrite the new refcount and return. If zero, munmap the executable page
    at offset 8 (trampoline_address) and deallocate the entry. The munmap
    length matches the page size used at registration (FFI_TRAMPOLINE_PAGE_SIZE).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1). The common refcount-positive path is one load, one subtract, one
    store. The final-release path adds one munmap (~3 microseconds) and one
    deallocate.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    munmap removes the executable mapping cleanly. After the call returns,
    the page address is no longer executable and cannot be reused without
    a fresh mmap -- this prevents use-after-free of the trampoline code.
    The entry pointer is invalid after a final-release decrement; callers
    that retained a copy must drop it.
    @End Security_Scope

    If entry is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ref be memory_get_int64(entry, 32)
    Set ref to ref minus 1

    If ref is greater than 0:
        memory_set_int64(entry, 32, ref)
        Return 1
    End If

    Let trampoline_addr be memory_get_int64(entry, 8)
    If trampoline_addr is not equal to 0:
        syscall_munmap(trampoline_addr, FFI_TRAMPOLINE_PAGE_SIZE)
    End If

    deallocate(entry)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "ffi_callback_get_trampoline_address" takes entry as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Accessor for the C-function-pointer trampoline address. Callers that
    pass a Runa closure across an FFI boundary supply the value returned
    from this accessor as the C function pointer argument; the C callee
    can call through it directly via the platform calling convention.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single 8-byte load from offset 8 of the callback entry. Returns 0 if
    entry is null, which the caller treats as "no callback available".
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) -- one memory load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Read-only accessor. The returned pointer is an executable address from
    a W^X-disciplined mmap region; the caller cannot write to it.
    @End Security_Scope

    If entry is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return memory_get_int64(entry, 8)
End Process

Process called "ffi_callback_get_closure_id" takes entry as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Accessor for the Runa closure identifier that this entry trampolines
    into. Used by introspection / debugging tooling to map a C function
    pointer back to its originating Runa closure.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single 8-byte load from offset 0 of the callback entry.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) -- one memory load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Read-only accessor. The closure_id is an opaque runtime identifier;
    leaking it does not expose memory layout.
    @End Security_Scope

    If entry is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return memory_get_int64(entry, 0)
End Process

Process called "ffi_callback_get_closure_env" takes entry as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Accessor for the captured-environment pointer that the trampoline loads
    into the dispatcher's first-arg register on every invocation. Returned
    by debugging tools and by the dispatcher itself when re-entering a
    closure body across an FFI boundary.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single 8-byte load from offset 16 of the callback entry.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) -- one memory load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Read-only accessor. The environment is owned by the Runa caller and
    must not be modified through the FFI boundary; this accessor returns
    the same pointer the trampoline embeds, so callers see the live state.
    @End Security_Scope

    If entry is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return memory_get_int64(entry, 16)
End Process

Process called "ffi_callback_retain" takes entry as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Increments the refcount on a shared callback entry. Used when multiple
    Runa code sites need to hold the same callback (e.g., when a callback
    pointer is stored in a long-lived data structure as well as passed to
    a one-shot C call).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Load-modify-store on offset 32. Returns the new refcount value.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) -- one load, one add, one store.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Refcount overflow is not a concern at any plausible runtime scale
    (2^63 retains would require centuries at one per nanosecond). The
    refcount is private to this manager; user FFI code cannot reach it
    except through retain / unregister.
    @End Security_Scope

    If entry is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ref be memory_get_int64(entry, 32)
    Set ref to ref plus 1
    memory_set_int64(entry, 32, ref)
    Return ref
End Process
